-And cold food as cold as the Antarctic.
-That gives you a brain freeze.

939
00:40:50,181 --> 00:40:52,650
You've hit that spot perfectly.

940
00:40:52,716 --> 00:40:54,452
Oh, my.

941
00:40:54,518 --> 00:40:57,288
-That chicken. Will you make a wrap?
-Stir-fried chicken.

942
00:40:57,354 --> 00:40:59,256
-Yes, please make it into a wrap.
-A wrap.

943
00:40:59,323 --> 00:41:01,892
-Use perilla leaf and lettuce.
-The wrap.

944
00:41:01,959 --> 00:41:03,761
And the salted cutlassfish innards.

945
00:41:03,828 --> 00:41:05,763
If the balance is perfect,
it'll be so good.

946
00:41:05,830 --> 00:41:09,633
Those are two vegetables
out of the few he likes.

947
00:41:09,700 --> 00:41:11,702
All my favorites are here.

948
00:41:11,769 --> 00:41:14,371
-Just those two.
-He doesn't like anything else.

949
00:41:15,039 --> 00:41:16,640
Look at that.

950
00:41:16,707 --> 00:41:18,409
The stir-fried chicken.

951
00:41:18,476 --> 00:41:21,111
That's Wrap-Wrap-Wrap-Wrap-lash.

952
00:41:21,178 --> 00:41:24,348
-He eats kimchi <i>jjigae </i>again.
-It must be good.

953
00:41:24,415 --> 00:41:27,384
-I know the taste, and it looks good.
-My mouth is watering.

954
00:41:27,451 --> 00:41:29,520
It's a full-course meal,

955
00:41:29,587 --> 00:41:31,856
so the second chef is at a disadvantage.

956
00:41:31,922 --> 00:41:36,026
Other than the main dishes,
I had the highest expectations

957
00:41:36,093 --> 00:41:38,796
for the lettuce <i>geotjeori</i>
and green onion salad.

958
00:41:40,331 --> 00:41:41,765
More than anything else,

959
00:41:41,832 --> 00:41:45,035
the dish that makes me feel like
I'm home is

960
00:41:45,102 --> 00:41:47,204
-green onion salad.
-I see.

961
00:41:47,271 --> 00:41:48,506
Please mix it well.

962
00:41:49,173 --> 00:41:50,908
-That's all about your cooking skills.
-Yes.

963
00:41:50,975 --> 00:41:54,144
-Yes, it has to be seasoned perfectly.
-Yes.

964
00:41:54,712 --> 00:41:57,414
This may be the game changer.

965
00:41:57,481 --> 00:41:59,550
He's smiling.

966
00:41:59,617 --> 00:42:01,685
Gosh, that looks good.

967
00:42:02,686 --> 00:42:04,188
-That's a good mix.
-Are you done?

968
00:42:04,255 --> 00:42:06,690
-Let me move on right away.
-Okay, right away.

969
00:42:06,757 --> 00:42:08,526
-We can't let the food get cold.
-No.

970
00:42:09,159 --> 00:42:13,097
This time, it's Chef Ho-young's
Pot-Pot-Pot-Pot-lash.

971
00:42:13,163 --> 00:42:16,967
THE SPICY BRAISED CHICKEN RECIPE
WATCHED 2 MILLION TIMES

972
00:42:17,635 --> 00:42:18,869
THE HIGHLY ANTICIPATED CHEMISTRY

973
00:42:18,936 --> 00:42:20,571
BETWEEN CHICKEN JEON
AND GREEN ONION SALAD

974
00:42:21,805 --> 00:42:25,376
CHEF JUNG HO-YOUNG'S
POT-POT-POT-POT-PLASH

975
00:42:25,442 --> 00:42:29,146
-It's the moment he opens that lid.
-That lid.

976
00:42:29,213 --> 00:42:31,682
-Shall we?
-Should we get it on camera?

977
00:42:31,749 --> 00:42:33,617
-It's hot.
-We'll get it on camera.

978
00:42:33,684 --> 00:42:34,685
Here it is!

979
00:42:34,752 --> 00:42:35,753
TA-DA

980
00:42:35,819 --> 00:42:36,820
Here it is!

981
00:42:36,887 --> 00:42:38,389
STEAMING WHITE RICE

982
00:42:38,455 --> 00:42:40,057
It's steaming hot.

983
00:42:40,124 --> 00:42:41,425
Was it cooked?

984
00:42:41,492 --> 00:42:43,594
-Is it undercooked?
-He should check.

985
00:42:43,661 --> 00:42:45,896
-Is it cooked?
-It's thoroughly cooked.

986
00:42:45,963 --> 00:42:47,464
It's cooked well.

987
00:42:47,531 --> 00:42:50,267
I live alone right now,

988
00:42:50,334 --> 00:42:52,269
and I eat pretty much one meal a day.

989
00:42:52,336 --> 00:42:55,139
And whenever I eat,
I always make fresh rice.

990
00:42:56,640 --> 00:42:58,442
-You don't eat leftover rice.
-No.

991
00:42:58,509 --> 00:42:59,510
-You're diligent.
-He's an epicure.

992
00:42:59,577 --> 00:43:02,613
So I like eating fresh rice like this.

993
00:43:04,048 --> 00:43:05,983
-He took a bite of just the rice.
-Yes.

994
00:43:06,050 --> 00:43:07,952
It can't compare to instant rice.

995
00:43:08,018 --> 00:43:10,721
-At times, just the rice is enough.
-Yes.

996
00:43:10,788 --> 00:43:12,489
Does he get extra points for that?

997
00:43:12,556 --> 00:43:13,891
It's different.

998
00:43:13,958 --> 00:43:17,995
There's a message
in the fact that he's eating just rice.

999
00:43:18,062 --> 00:43:19,229
LOOKS

1000
00:43:20,731 --> 00:43:22,066
ANXIOUS, SMILING

1001
00:43:22,132 --> 00:43:23,434
This is bad.

1002
00:43:24,001 --> 00:43:26,770
HE MUST BE HAPPY
WITH THE STONE POT RICE

1003
00:43:26,837 --> 00:43:28,772
You can eat just rice
when the rice is delicious.

1004
00:43:29,473 --> 00:43:31,342
-The braised chicken.
-I wonder how the sauce is.

1005
00:43:31,408 --> 00:43:34,311
This is the spicy braised chicken recipe
that was viewed two million times.

1006
00:43:34,378 --> 00:43:36,347
-It does look thick.
-Yes.

1007
00:43:36,413 --> 00:43:38,916
Back there, it was just too sweet.

1008
00:43:38,983 --> 00:43:42,119
-Everyone is gulping.
-I wonder if it tastes savory.

1009
00:43:42,186 --> 00:43:45,189
He puts the rice in the sauce again.

1010
00:43:45,255 --> 00:43:48,292
-He must like doing that.
-He knows what's good.

1011
00:43:49,727 --> 00:43:52,463
-How about the next one?
-Look at that.

1012
00:43:52,529 --> 00:43:56,300
His mother would be happy
to see him eat his food deliciously.

1013
00:43:56,367 --> 00:44:00,237
I love how it burns
as the freshly cooked rice goes down.

1014
00:44:00,304 --> 00:44:01,572
-Yes.
-It burns.

1015
00:44:01,639 --> 00:44:03,374
-It burns your throat.
-Yes.

1016
00:44:03,440 --> 00:44:05,075
It feels dynamic in there.

1017
00:44:05,142 --> 00:44:07,177
Try a drumstick.

1018
00:44:08,112 --> 00:44:11,382
-I want to try everything.
-Yes.

1019
00:44:11,448 --> 00:44:12,716
He must be full.

1020
00:44:12,783 --> 00:44:15,819
My eyes almost feel bloodshot.
It's that strong.

1021
00:44:15,886 --> 00:44:17,888
It creates that pressure.

1022
00:44:17,955 --> 00:44:19,923
-You like it extremely hot or cold.
-Yes.

1023
00:44:19,990 --> 00:44:23,560
Top the chicken <i>jeon</i>
with the green onion salad.

1024
00:44:23,627 --> 00:44:27,464
The one in the bottom center
is always the strongest.

1025
00:44:27,531 --> 00:44:31,001
-I see.
-I'll mix it a little.

1026
00:44:31,969 --> 00:44:34,038
He eats so deliciously.

1027
00:44:34,972 --> 00:44:36,840
You'll eat that in one bite?

1028
00:44:36,907 --> 00:44:38,676
A BIG BITE

1029
00:44:38,742 --> 00:44:42,279
My son, you've worked so hard
while you were in Seoul.

1030
00:44:42,346 --> 00:44:45,649
Hey, DEX, I can tell that
you're enjoying it very much,

1031
00:44:45,716 --> 00:44:48,285
but can you give us a review?
I'm dying to know.

1032
00:44:48,352 --> 00:44:51,722
I'm dying to know how good it is
as I watch you eat everything.

1033
00:44:51,789 --> 00:44:53,457
-We all know what that tastes like.
-Yes.

1034
00:44:53,524 --> 00:44:54,958
-So it drives me crazier.
-I'm curious.

1035
00:44:55,025 --> 00:44:57,027
You can't eat
green onion salad like this in Seoul.

1036
00:44:57,094 --> 00:44:58,095
Really?

1037
00:44:58,829 --> 00:45:02,633
-This green onion salad is in Suncheon.
-I see.

1038
00:45:02,700 --> 00:45:04,435
-It's as if he's eating that in Suncheon.
-The greatest compliment.

1039
00:45:04,501 --> 00:45:06,470
The green onion salad in Suncheon

1040
00:45:06,537 --> 00:45:10,007
uses a generous amount of sesame oil.

1041
00:45:10,074 --> 00:45:13,510
This lettuce <i>geotjeori</i>

1042
00:45:13,577 --> 00:45:16,213
-is something I had often in Seoul.
-I see.

1043
00:45:16,280 --> 00:45:20,117
But this green onion salad
is a taste from my hometown.

1044
00:45:20,184 --> 00:45:22,319
When I go back home, my grandma

1045
00:45:22,386 --> 00:45:27,057
would pour in lots of sesame oil
and mix everything with her hand.

1046
00:45:27,758 --> 00:45:32,463
He used the sesame oil
in that soju bottle.

1047
00:45:32,529 --> 00:45:34,732
-It's from his hometown.
-Yes.

1048
00:45:34,798 --> 00:45:37,000
That's the taste of my hometown.

1049
00:45:37,067 --> 00:45:38,736
You were right on.

1050
00:45:38,802 --> 00:45:44,308
I think the main dishes
were braised chicken and kimchi <i>jjigae</i>.

1051
00:45:44,374 --> 00:45:48,011
Did you add butter
to this braised chicken?

1052
00:45:48,078 --> 00:45:52,783
I used bone broth to add a deeper flavor
in a short period of time.

1053
00:45:52,850 --> 00:45:54,651
That added to the depth.

1054
00:45:54,718 --> 00:45:56,820
It felt a bit odd

1055
00:45:56,887 --> 00:46:01,291
that the braised chicken
had that fragrance of butter.

1056
00:46:01,358 --> 00:46:06,897
But this kimchi <i>jjigae </i>tasted
better and better with each bite.

1057
00:46:06,964 --> 00:46:10,701
So it felt so addictive
when I had it with rice.

1058
00:46:10,768 --> 00:46:13,604
It was very similar
to something that my mother made.

1059
00:46:13,670 --> 00:46:16,340
I liked how strong it tasted.

1060
00:46:16,406 --> 00:46:19,343
-That's all for me.
-Okay.

1061
00:46:19,843 --> 00:46:21,445
Should we try some too?

1062
00:46:21,512 --> 00:46:24,348
We're trying Chef Sam's dishes now.

1063
00:46:25,349 --> 00:46:28,152
We're trying Chef Sam's food.

1064
00:46:29,219 --> 00:46:32,389
Hey, it has a strong flavor.

1065
00:46:32,456 --> 00:46:34,691
-Excellent job. It's good.
-Kimchi <i>jjigae</i>?

1066
00:46:34,758 --> 00:46:38,629
-The kimchi <i>jjigae</i> is really good.
-Really?

1067
00:46:38,695 --> 00:46:41,031
-It has a strong flavor.
-It does?

1068
00:46:41,098 --> 00:46:44,301
The earthen pot adds more flavor
as time passes by.

1069
00:46:44,368 --> 00:46:45,769
It's still warm.

1070
00:46:46,336 --> 00:46:48,372
Next, Chef Ho-young's braised chicken.

1071
00:46:49,973 --> 00:46:51,542
Gosh, it's good.

1072
00:46:52,943 --> 00:46:55,712
-The potatoes are cooked perfectly.
-The potatoes are good.

1073
00:46:55,779 --> 00:46:59,616
It'll be game over
if you mix rice into this.

1074
00:46:59,683 --> 00:47:02,052
I thought he would've messed up
the braised chicken.

1075
00:47:02,119 --> 00:47:05,589
I didn't think
he had enough time to finish it.

1076
00:47:05,656 --> 00:47:06,690
But it's really good.

1077
00:47:06,757 --> 00:47:10,260
I see why it was viewed two million times.

1078
00:47:10,327 --> 00:47:12,462
-It's tender and delicious.
-Right?

1079
00:47:12,529 --> 00:47:14,731
-It'll be hard to choose.
-It is. It's very hard.

1080
00:47:14,798 --> 00:47:17,734
Amazing Jeolla-style full-course meal.

1081
00:47:17,801 --> 00:47:21,505
Press one for Sam Kim's
Wrap-Wrap-Wrap-Wrap-lash.

1082
00:47:21,572 --> 00:47:24,575
Press two for Jung Ho-young's
Pot-Pot-Pot-Pot-lash.

1083
00:47:24,641 --> 00:47:27,611
Please make your decision
and press the button.

1084
00:47:28,378 --> 00:47:30,280
This is a hard one.

1085
00:47:32,249 --> 00:47:35,118
-Did you press one?
-I did.

1086
00:47:35,185 --> 00:47:37,487
DEX has made his choice.

1087
00:47:37,554 --> 00:47:42,626
Which one of the two was more amazing
as a Jeolla-style full-course meal?

1088
00:47:42,693 --> 00:47:44,528
Will Ho-young win once again?

1089
00:47:44,595 --> 00:47:46,630
Or will Sam get his revenge?

1090
00:47:46,697 --> 00:47:48,799
-What's the result?
-What's the result?

1091
00:47:48,866 --> 00:47:50,000
Who won?

1092
00:47:50,067 --> 00:47:53,003
Will it be Ho-young or Sam?

1093
00:47:53,070 --> 00:47:55,105
Who did DEX choose? Let's find out!

1094
00:47:55,172 --> 00:47:57,407
JUNG HO-YOUNG WINS

1095
00:47:57,474 --> 00:47:58,909
Let's find out!

1096
00:47:58,976 --> 00:48:00,644
CHEF JUNG HO-YOUNG'S
POT-POT-POT-POT-LASH WINS

1097
00:48:00,711 --> 00:48:02,479
Jung Ho-young wins!

1098
00:48:02,546 --> 00:48:03,547
Jung Ho-young!

1099
00:48:03,614 --> 00:48:04,748
JUNG HO-YOUNG WINS ONCE AGAIN

1100
00:48:04,815 --> 00:48:07,651
The full-course meal. Gosh.

1101
00:48:07,718 --> 00:48:11,121
-He knew the Jeolla-style.
-It's hard to beat him.

1102
00:48:11,188 --> 00:48:15,759
Both meals were equally good,
but there was one difference.

1103
00:48:15,826 --> 00:48:21,131
The stone pot rice
was cooked perfectly to my liking.

1104
00:48:21,198 --> 00:48:22,232
You're right.

1105
00:48:22,299 --> 00:48:27,371
Also, this green onion salad
was the highlight.

1106
00:48:27,437 --> 00:48:29,840
I see. What was it called again?

1107
00:48:29,907 --> 00:48:33,343
<i>Pot-Pot-Pot-Pot-lash</i>

1108
00:48:33,410 --> 00:48:35,979
-Yes, excellent job.
-Thank you.

1109
00:48:36,046 --> 00:48:39,383
A star goes to Chef Ho-young!

1110
00:48:39,449 --> 00:48:40,584
He takes his third win.

1111
00:48:40,651 --> 00:48:41,985
Congratulations.

1112
00:48:42,052 --> 00:48:45,455
He gets his third star. Congratulations.

1113
00:48:45,522 --> 00:48:46,957
-Congratulations.
-Thank you.

1114
00:48:47,457 --> 00:48:48,692
CHEF & MY FRIDGE

1115
00:48:49,459 --> 00:48:51,895
<i>Hello, passengers.</i>

1116
00:48:51,962 --> 00:48:56,833
I'm Pilot Kim Sung-ju,
here to fly you to Suncheon,

1117
00:48:56,900 --> 00:48:59,169
Jeolla Province.

1118
00:48:59,236 --> 00:49:01,138
Here on <i>Chef & My Fridge </i>Air,

1119
00:49:01,204 --> 00:49:05,008
we have a valued guest, DEX,
the son of Suncheon, with us.

1120
00:49:05,642 --> 00:49:06,643
LOOKS

1121
00:49:07,144 --> 00:49:09,446
The flight attendant…

1122
00:49:09,513 --> 00:49:11,214
Are you a steward or a stewardess?

1123
00:49:11,281 --> 00:49:12,582
I'm uncertain.

1124
00:49:12,649 --> 00:49:14,851
I'll be a stewardo.

1125
00:49:14,918 --> 00:49:16,620
I'm not a steward or a stewardess.

1126
00:49:16,687 --> 00:49:20,057
-Straighten that out.
-I'm here to serve our guests.

1127
00:49:20,123 --> 00:49:22,426
-I'm at your service.
-Okay.

1128
00:49:22,492 --> 00:49:27,297
This next battle is between Kwon Sung-jun,
the winner of <i>Culinary Class Wars,</i>

1129
00:49:27,364 --> 00:49:32,202
and Cook of the Darkness,
Webtoon Artist Kim Poong.

1130
00:49:32,269 --> 00:49:38,275
You two had an ongoing story about Sylvia.

1131
00:49:38,342 --> 00:49:39,910
-Sylvia?
-Yes.

1132
00:49:39,977 --> 00:49:44,281
-I don't know what Sylvia is.
-He doesn't know anymore.

1133
00:49:44,348 --> 00:49:46,383
-Already?
-I have a new friend now.

1134
00:49:46,450 --> 00:49:49,152
-You have a new friend?
-That looks cool.

1135
00:49:49,219 --> 00:49:52,155
-This is made of copper…
-It's pretty.

1136
00:49:52,222 --> 00:49:53,323
…so it's called Copperel.

1137
00:49:53,390 --> 00:49:56,059
-Copperel. That's its name?
-That's right.

1138
00:49:56,126 --> 00:49:57,861
-Copperel?
-It looks heavy.

1139
00:49:57,928 --> 00:50:01,031
I'm going to get a fresh start
with this pan.

1140
00:50:01,098 --> 00:50:05,002
He wants to open a new era of the show
with Copperel.

1141
00:50:05,068 --> 00:50:07,437
If you lose today,

1142
00:50:07,504 --> 00:50:09,039
will you hand it over?

1143
00:50:09,106 --> 00:50:11,675
-But this pan, Copperel…
-Yes?

1144
00:50:11,742 --> 00:50:14,644
…was about six to seven times
more expensive than Sylvia.

1145
00:50:15,545 --> 00:50:16,947
Did you get it recently?

1146
00:50:17,014 --> 00:50:18,982
-Yes. I have to use it for life.
-It looks new.

1147
00:50:19,049 --> 00:50:20,684
-I see.
-It is new.

1148
00:50:20,751 --> 00:50:22,419
It looks a bit heavy, though. Is it okay?

1149
00:50:22,486 --> 00:50:25,222
It's very heavy.
Do you want to feel it, DEX?

1150
00:50:25,288 --> 00:50:27,958
-Should I do that?
-Try to feel how heavy it is.

1151
00:50:28,025 --> 00:50:30,327
-He makes it look very light.
-It must be a few kilograms.

1152
00:50:32,195 --> 00:50:34,831
Come on. He's such an entertainer.

1153
00:50:34,898 --> 00:50:36,967
-Isn't it heavy?
-But yes, it's quite heavy.

1154
00:50:37,034 --> 00:50:38,902
He might hurt his wrists.

1155
00:50:38,969 --> 00:50:40,137
-Really?
-Really?

1156
00:50:40,203 --> 00:50:43,707
Poong, do you have
anything special to say?

1157
00:50:44,574 --> 00:50:46,176
-Nope.
-No.

1158
00:50:46,243 --> 00:50:47,744
It'd be odd if he had anything.

1159
00:50:47,811 --> 00:50:50,147
-I should've brought something.
-Right.

1160
00:50:51,081 --> 00:50:53,083
CHEF SUNG-JUN: THOUSAND ISLAND DRESSING,
CREAM CHEESE CHERRY PEPPER, MILK, POTATO,

1161
00:50:53,150 --> 00:50:55,152
LETTUCE, KIWI, LIME JUICE, CHOCOLATE BALL,
CORN SOUP POWDER, TENDERLOIN, AND MORE

1162
00:50:55,218 --> 00:50:57,587
The name of my in-flight meal is

1163
00:50:58,255 --> 00:50:59,389
Milan Matfia.

1164
00:50:59,456 --> 00:51:01,291
-I see.
-"Milan Matfia"?

1165
00:51:01,358 --> 00:51:02,592
Not Napoli?

1166
00:51:02,659 --> 00:51:06,363
Think of it as a meal you'll have
on the flight back from Milan.

1167
00:51:07,230 --> 00:51:09,833
I thought he should eat
a nutritionally balanced meal,

1168
00:51:09,900 --> 00:51:13,703
so I wanted to make polenta,
a type of corn porridge they eat in Milan.

1169
00:51:13,770 --> 00:51:17,107
-I'll top it with meat and potatoes.
-Milan.

1170
00:51:17,174 --> 00:51:19,776
I'll also make a chicken sandwich
for your protein intake

1171
00:51:19,843 --> 00:51:21,378
along with a special sauce.

1172
00:51:21,445 --> 00:51:23,146
-And a sandwich?
-As dessert,

1173
00:51:23,213 --> 00:51:26,283
I want to prepare yogurt ice cream,
the biggest fad right now.

1174
00:51:26,349 --> 00:51:28,018
-I see.
-Yogurt ice cream?

1175
00:51:28,085 --> 00:51:30,487
-It's a course meal.
-It is.

1176
00:51:31,421 --> 00:51:33,423
ARTIST POONG'S INGREDIENTS:
SHRIMP HEADS, SIRLOIN, HOTDOG BUN

1177
00:51:33,490 --> 00:51:35,492
CHICKEN STOCK, LETTUCE,
PERILLA LEAF, AND MILK

1178
00:51:35,559 --> 00:51:39,396
Up against him is Webtoon Artist Poong.
What's your in-flight meal?

1179
00:51:40,030 --> 00:51:41,031
One, two.

1180
00:51:56,847 --> 00:51:58,515
"Attention Poong-lease"?

1181
00:51:58,582 --> 00:52:00,250
It's called Attention Poong-lease.

1182
00:52:00,317 --> 00:52:02,319
-I see.
-"Attention Poong-lease."

1183
00:52:02,385 --> 00:52:05,856
He and I have different ideas
when it comes to in-flight meals.

1184
00:52:05,922 --> 00:52:08,158
I believe it must be high in calories.

1185
00:52:08,225 --> 00:52:10,794
You have to give them a blood sugar spike
and put them to sleep.

1186
00:52:12,729 --> 00:52:16,166
-They need to put as many people to sleep…
-A blood sugar spike?

1187
00:52:16,233 --> 00:52:19,035
…to do their jobs much more easily.

1188
00:52:19,102 --> 00:52:23,340
-So overall, that's why it tastes strong.
-He has a point.

1189
00:52:23,406 --> 00:52:27,110
You didn't consult an airline
to prepare for what you just said, right?

1190
00:52:27,177 --> 00:52:29,579
-It's your idea, right?
-It is.

1191
00:52:29,646 --> 00:52:32,516
And the flight is headed to America.

1192
00:52:32,582 --> 00:52:33,984
-Are we flying to America?
-Yes.

1193
00:52:34,050 --> 00:52:38,121
You can find all kinds of
international dishes in America.

1194
00:52:38,188 --> 00:52:42,159
And one of the in-flight meals
I remember eating

1195
00:52:42,225 --> 00:52:43,960
served Mongolian beef.

1196
00:52:44,027 --> 00:52:46,096
-I see. Mongolian beef over rice.
-Yes.

1197
00:52:46,163 --> 00:52:49,499
I'll also serve soup and bread
along with the main dish.

1198
00:52:49,566 --> 00:52:51,368
I'll make perilla leaf soup.

1199
00:52:51,434 --> 00:52:52,736
Perilla leaf soup?

1200
00:52:52,802 --> 00:52:53,937
-Perilla leaf soup?
-There's perilla leaf soup?

1201
00:52:54,004 --> 00:52:56,206
-I'll make perilla leaf cream soup.
-I see.

1202
00:52:56,273 --> 00:52:58,842
I don't think DEX is too thrilled.

1203
00:52:58,909 --> 00:53:01,178
I think I booked with the wrong airline.

1204
00:53:01,244 --> 00:53:03,680
Why did you suddenly come up
with perilla leaf soup?

1205
00:53:03,747 --> 00:53:07,083
I thought, "This is K-herb."

1206
00:53:07,150 --> 00:53:10,053
I've been pushing it a little.

1207
00:53:10,120 --> 00:53:11,388
What else?

1208
00:53:11,454 --> 00:53:13,190
<i>Kouign-amann</i>, a French dessert.

1209
00:53:13,256 --> 00:53:14,758
-A French dessert.
-<i>Kouign-amann</i>?

1210
00:53:14,824 --> 00:53:16,526
-<i>Kouign-amann</i>?
-He's making <i>kouign-amann</i>?

1211
00:53:16,593 --> 00:53:17,594
What's <i>kouign-amann</i>?

1212
00:53:17,661 --> 00:53:21,932
It's a type of pastry
made with lots of sugar and butter.

1213
00:53:21,998 --> 00:53:24,134
-<i>Kouign-amann</i>?
-You're making that?

1214
00:53:24,201 --> 00:53:25,936
But I don't think I can do that.

1215
00:53:27,871 --> 00:53:29,873
-What are you talking about?
-It's in my head, though.

1216
00:53:29,940 --> 00:53:31,841
It's there. It's in my head.

1217
00:53:31,908 --> 00:53:34,511
People will lodge complaints
if you leave out some food.

1218
00:53:34,578 --> 00:53:35,946
Of course.

1219
00:53:36,012 --> 00:53:38,848
It means he didn't serve it
even though it was on the menu.

1220
00:53:38,915 --> 00:53:40,684
-Yes, think about it.
-He has to make it.

1221
00:53:40,750 --> 00:53:43,420
-I'll do it.
-It's not like he ran out.

1222
00:53:43,486 --> 00:53:44,487
-Will you?
-He has to do it.

1223
00:53:44,554 --> 00:53:45,789
-All right. I'll do it.
-Okay.

1224
00:53:45,855 --> 00:53:47,357
-You have to serve something.
-I'll do it.

1225
00:53:47,424 --> 00:53:50,060
-All right.
-Let's do it. Let's go.

1226
00:53:50,126 --> 00:53:52,128
-Hurry up.
-Let us begin the in-flight meal round.

1227
00:53:52,195 --> 00:53:53,897
-Watch your hand.
-He's in a hurry.

1228
00:53:53,964 --> 00:53:55,865
He's scary.

1229
00:53:55,932 --> 00:53:59,536
-I'm going to cook.
-That's scary.

1230
00:53:59,603 --> 00:54:01,538
You have to move quickly
because of the dessert.

1231
00:54:01,605 --> 00:54:05,375
I have to move quickly.
Darn it! Why did I bring up the dessert?

1232
00:54:05,442 --> 00:54:07,143
I have to introduce the round.

1233
00:54:07,210 --> 00:54:09,679
All right. That knife really is scary.

1234
00:54:11,014 --> 00:54:14,317
All right. He's going to pick up
his identity as a knockoff chef

1235
00:54:14,384 --> 00:54:16,620
and aim to start a winning streak,

1236
00:54:16,686 --> 00:54:18,755
the old school of the show,
Webtoon Artist Kim Poong.

1237
00:54:18,822 --> 00:54:20,490
HE NOTICED SOMETHING

1238
00:54:20,557 --> 00:54:21,558
LAUGHING

1239
00:54:22,058 --> 00:54:23,226
What's with him?

1240
00:54:23,293 --> 00:54:28,365
This man brought the catfish pan,
Copperel, to shake the show around.

1241
00:54:28,431 --> 00:54:32,235
The catfish chef of the show,
Chef Kwon Sung-jun.

1242
00:54:32,302 --> 00:54:36,206
Which one of them
will capture DEX's heart?

1243
00:54:36,273 --> 00:54:40,110
Let the in-flight meal round begin!

1244
00:54:42,012 --> 00:54:43,847
SUNG-JUN RUNS
TO THE FREEZER RIGHT AWAY

1245
00:54:43,913 --> 00:54:45,181
HE TAKES THE ICE CREAM!

1246
00:54:45,749 --> 00:54:47,884
POONG GRABS THE BREAD FIRST

1247
00:54:48,451 --> 00:54:51,254
They need to use every second.
All right, he's cutting the bread.

1248
00:54:51,321 --> 00:54:53,156
Will that bread turn into <i>kouign-amann</i>?

1249
00:54:53,223 --> 00:54:55,325
-No, not this.
-Why did you cut it?

1250
00:54:55,392 --> 00:54:56,793
DASHING

1251
00:54:56,860 --> 00:54:57,861
What are you doing?

1252
00:54:57,927 --> 00:54:58,995
Why is he using that oven?

1253
00:54:59,062 --> 00:55:01,097
The oven isn't on.

1254
00:55:01,164 --> 00:55:02,632
SUNG-JUN TAKES
TWO SCOOPS OF ICE CREAM

1255
00:55:03,900 --> 00:55:05,235
Is the oven on? No?

1256
00:55:05,302 --> 00:55:06,636
-No?
-I don't know.

1257
00:55:06,703 --> 00:55:08,338
-Are you serious?
-I don't know.

1258
00:55:08,405 --> 00:55:09,906
PREHEAT

1259
00:55:10,473 --> 00:55:12,342
-Oh, no.
-What's going on?

1260
00:55:12,409 --> 00:55:14,811
-What's happening?
-No idea.

1261
00:55:14,878 --> 00:55:17,681
Why is it preheating now?
Man, I'm doomed.

1262
00:55:17,747 --> 00:55:20,050
-Why did they cross?
-Why did they switch?

1263
00:55:20,116 --> 00:55:22,085
Why did you use the oven
on the opposite side?

1264
00:55:22,152 --> 00:55:23,720
-You had one closer.
-Because we both have to use

1265
00:55:23,787 --> 00:55:25,522
the microwave and the oven.

1266
00:55:25,588 --> 00:55:27,991
I see. One of them is the microwave
and the other is the oven.

1267
00:55:28,058 --> 00:55:31,194
That's used as a microwave,
and that's used as an oven.

1268
00:55:32,195 --> 00:55:34,564
Was there a reason
why you put the bread in the oven?

1269
00:55:36,032 --> 00:55:37,534
He won't even answer me.

1270
00:55:37,600 --> 00:55:39,536
-He's busy trying to get to dessert.
-Yes.

1271
00:55:39,602 --> 00:55:41,371
I see.

1272
00:55:41,438 --> 00:55:43,640
SUNG-JUN PREPARES THE DESSERT FIRST

1273
00:55:44,307 --> 00:55:47,043
Chef Sung-jun,
what did you throw into the freezer?

1274
00:55:47,110 --> 00:55:48,278
It's the yogurt ice cream.

1275
00:55:48,345 --> 00:55:50,547
The yogurt ice cream. Already?

1276
00:55:50,613 --> 00:55:52,549
So he had yogurt.

1277
00:55:52,615 --> 00:55:54,951
He's using meat. What is it?

1278
00:55:55,018 --> 00:55:56,419
-I think it's sirloin.
-Sirloin.

1279
00:55:58,488 --> 00:56:02,926
1. MIX SIRLOIN WITH SOY SAUCE,
COOKING WINE, AND STARCH

1280
00:56:03,426 --> 00:56:04,961
Okay. How long has it been?

1281
00:56:05,028 --> 00:56:06,796
-Tell me when to take the bread out.
-Not yet.

1282
00:56:08,198 --> 00:56:09,833
What is he muttering about?

1283
00:56:09,899 --> 00:56:11,067
He asked me for two favors.

1284
00:56:11,134 --> 00:56:13,837
Take the bread out after three minutes.
Warm the rice at five minutes.

1285
00:56:13,903 --> 00:56:15,872
-He asked you to tell him?
-I see.

1286
00:56:15,939 --> 00:56:18,341
-He's frying something. Is that beef?
-Yes.

1287
00:56:18,408 --> 00:56:20,276
-Sirloin.
-Sirloin.

1288
00:56:20,343 --> 00:56:22,245
Mongolian beef is made

1289
00:56:22,312 --> 00:56:25,181
by frying beef and mixing it
with a soy-sauce based sauce.

1290
00:56:25,248 --> 00:56:28,852
Many people enjoy it,
so it's often served on flights.

1291
00:56:29,519 --> 00:56:30,520
KEEPING AN EYE ON HIM

1292
00:56:32,122 --> 00:56:34,090
Wow, he's fast.

1293
00:56:34,958 --> 00:56:36,659
Gosh, that's scary.

1294
00:56:37,227 --> 00:56:39,229
HE CHOPS THE ONION IN A FLASH

1295
00:56:39,963 --> 00:56:41,364
There's Copperel.

1296
00:56:41,431 --> 00:56:42,999
-Copperel.
-Copperel.

1297
00:56:43,066 --> 00:56:44,467
COPPEREL IS IN THE PICTURE

1298
00:56:44,534 --> 00:56:47,303
Copperel with high thermal conductivity.

1299
00:56:47,370 --> 00:56:49,339
He didn't heat up his pan.

1300
00:56:49,406 --> 00:56:52,142
-It must be the thermal conductivity.
-It's quite high.

1301
00:56:52,208 --> 00:56:54,544
He's frying garlic. Is that garlic?

1302
00:56:54,611 --> 00:56:57,747
-I think it's onion.
-It's onion?

1303
00:56:57,814 --> 00:56:59,349
Is that milk?

1304
00:56:59,416 --> 00:57:03,119
-Bone broth.
-Bone broth. And milk.

1305
00:57:03,186 --> 00:57:05,021
He said he'd make polenta,

1306
00:57:05,088 --> 00:57:06,923
and he needs yellow ground corn
to do that.

1307
00:57:06,990 --> 00:57:11,828
You mix that with milk and butter
and turn it into porridge.

1308
00:57:11,895 --> 00:57:13,029
Do you have ground corn?

1309
00:57:13,096 --> 00:57:15,231
No, I don't think I have that.

1310
00:57:15,298 --> 00:57:16,699
What will he use, then?

1311
00:57:16,766 --> 00:57:18,067
Are you making sweet and sour beef?

1312
00:57:19,636 --> 00:57:20,637
LAUGHING

1313
00:57:20,703 --> 00:57:23,640
Poong, did you decide to change the meal
to sweet and sour beef?

1314
00:57:23,706 --> 00:57:24,741
No.

1315
00:57:24,808 --> 00:57:26,776
-Isn't the sirloin overcooked?
-No.

1316
00:57:26,843 --> 00:57:28,912
It looks burnt.

1317
00:57:28,978 --> 00:57:31,080
I wonder how it'll turn out.

1318
00:57:31,147 --> 00:57:33,416
-It does look crunchy.
-It does.

1319
00:57:33,483 --> 00:57:36,386
-I hope the meal is good for our guest.
-Indeed.

1320
00:57:37,554 --> 00:57:38,721
ADDING BEEF FLAVOR

1321
00:57:39,989 --> 00:57:42,759
3. MAKE GREEN ONION OIL
WITH THE BEEF-FLAVORED OIL

1322
00:57:43,326 --> 00:57:45,261
RUSTLING

1323
00:57:45,829 --> 00:57:47,063
THIS IS…

1324
00:57:47,130 --> 00:57:48,431
Is that corn soup?

1325
00:57:49,132 --> 00:57:51,100
-He's using corn soup powder.
-To make polenta.

1326
00:57:51,167 --> 00:57:52,769
-I see.
-He's using that.

1327
00:57:52,836 --> 00:57:54,070
What's that powder?

1328
00:57:54,137 --> 00:57:55,405
-Corn soup.
-Corn soup.

1329
00:57:55,472 --> 00:57:58,041
-It's usually mixed with water.
-Oh, corn soup.

1330
00:57:58,107 --> 00:57:59,409
FULLY CONVINCED

1331
00:57:59,476 --> 00:58:01,177
He's making polenta with that.

1332
00:58:01,244 --> 00:58:03,513
-It's corn powder, so it makes sense.
-It does.

1333
00:58:05,748 --> 00:58:07,283
CONTROLLING THE THICKNESS
WITH WATER

1334
00:58:07,784 --> 00:58:09,552
A TUB WITH GREEK YOGURT

1335
00:58:09,619 --> 00:58:11,521
MUSTARD, THOUSAND ISLAND,
OLIVE OIL, LIME JUICE

1336
00:58:11,588 --> 00:58:12,989
What are you making, Chef Sung-jun?

1337
00:58:13,056 --> 00:58:16,125
-Sandwich dressing.
-Sandwich dressing.

1338
00:58:16,192 --> 00:58:17,994
-That looks good.
-He's adding lots of stuff.

1339
00:58:18,061 --> 00:58:19,562
Yes, he's putting in a lot.

1340
00:58:19,629 --> 00:58:22,999
We get a lot of sauce
on our flight back from Milan.

1341
00:58:23,066 --> 00:58:25,502
-Pull out the bread.
-What? Okay.

1342
00:58:26,069 --> 00:58:29,672
4. FRY SHRIMP HEADS
IN GREEN ONION OIL

1343
00:58:30,240 --> 00:58:32,509
TIME TO PULL THE BREAD OUT
FROM THE OVEN

1344
00:58:34,344 --> 00:58:36,112
What? It's not hot at all.

1345
00:58:36,179 --> 00:58:37,413
RETURNS FOR NOW

1346
00:58:37,480 --> 00:58:40,517
-Why are you running around?
-What's with that? Does that oven work?

1347
00:58:40,583 --> 00:58:41,718
Probably.

1348
00:58:41,784 --> 00:58:42,919
Damn it.

1349
00:58:42,986 --> 00:58:44,621
Well, I don't know.

1350
00:58:44,687 --> 00:58:47,357
Artist Poong,
your flight is experiencing turbulence.

1351
00:58:47,423 --> 00:58:49,092
Do not run on the plane.

1352
00:58:50,593 --> 00:58:52,262
Do you have trouble checking on the oven?

1353
00:58:54,497 --> 00:58:56,032
Damn it.

1354
00:58:56,099 --> 00:58:57,667
TRYING TO GET BUTTER THE 2ND TIME

1355
00:58:58,968 --> 00:59:00,470
Damn it.

1356
00:59:00,537 --> 00:59:02,005
NOTHING WORKS OUT
WHEN HE FEELS RUSHED

1357
00:59:02,071 --> 00:59:03,473
-He's let himself go.
-Oh, no.

1358
00:59:03,540 --> 00:59:06,442
You have to press the start button
if you want to get the oven going.

1359
00:59:06,509 --> 00:59:07,877
Damn it.

1360
00:59:08,611 --> 00:59:10,046
THE FLIGHT TO AMERICA
IS FULL OF PROFANITY

1361
00:59:10,113 --> 00:59:12,815
You have to press start
whenever you open it and close it.

1362
00:59:12,882 --> 00:59:14,384
You have to press the start button.

1363
00:59:14,450 --> 00:59:15,618
Flour.

1364
00:59:15,685 --> 00:59:16,819
DO NOT RUN ON A PLANE

1365
00:59:16,886 --> 00:59:19,088
I don't think
he'll even finish the Mongolian beef.

1366
00:59:20,523 --> 00:59:22,225
5. MIX BUTTER, GARLIC AND FLOUR
IN THE GREEN ONION OIL, MAKE ROUX

1367
00:59:22,292 --> 00:59:23,293
He's making roux.

1368
00:59:23,359 --> 00:59:25,361
-That'll turn into soup, right?
-Yes.

1369
00:59:25,428 --> 00:59:28,064
-He's making roux right now.
-Roux.

1370
00:59:28,131 --> 00:59:31,000
He cooked shrimp head in butter
and also added flour.

1371
00:59:31,067 --> 00:59:33,136
He's doing it the proper way.

1372
00:59:35,672 --> 00:59:37,774
I have to use the oven too.

1373
00:59:37,840 --> 00:59:39,475
What do we do about the oven?

1374
00:59:39,542 --> 00:59:41,377
-I don't know.
-I need to use it too.

1375
00:59:41,444 --> 00:59:43,479
I need… I'm doomed. Hold on.

1376
00:59:43,546 --> 00:59:46,783
-Oh, no.
-Why wasn't the oven ready?

1377
00:59:46,849 --> 00:59:49,152
I'll do it for you guys. Keep cooking.

1378
00:59:49,819 --> 00:59:51,120
What should I set the temperature to?

1379
00:59:51,187 --> 00:59:52,555
-Set it to 180 degrees.
-Okay.

1380
00:59:53,423 --> 00:59:55,858
Will it get that hot right now?
To 180 degrees?

1381
00:59:55,925 --> 00:59:56,993
I don't think so.

1382
00:59:57,060 --> 00:59:59,329
-Is 185 degrees okay?
-They should've done it beforehand.

1383
00:59:59,395 --> 01:00:00,897
I'm looking forward to this.

1384
01:00:00,964 --> 01:00:03,132
It's more intriguing
because things aren't going as planned.

1385
01:00:03,199 --> 01:00:06,069
Things are a mess right now.

1386
01:00:06,135 --> 01:00:07,236
<i>Kouign-amann</i>

1387
01:00:07,303 --> 01:00:13,309
is one of the crunchiest and sweetest
pastries, coated with a sugar glaze.

1388
01:00:13,376 --> 01:00:15,078
-That sounds good.
-But he didn't have any pastry.

1389
01:00:15,144 --> 01:00:17,213
I wonder how he's going to make it<i>.</i>

1390
01:00:17,280 --> 01:00:19,415
-I wonder.
-He'll probably just put sugar on bread.

1391
01:00:19,482 --> 01:00:21,050
That's just sugar on bread,
not <i>kouign-amann</i>.

1392
01:00:21,117 --> 01:00:22,619
It's more like <i>kkwabaegi</i>.

1393
01:00:22,685 --> 01:00:25,288
It has to be pastry,
where you can feel every layer.

1394
01:00:26,923 --> 01:00:28,958
He's using another type of bread.

1395
01:00:29,025 --> 01:00:31,427
-He's using a croissant.
-He had pastry.

1396
01:00:31,494 --> 01:00:32,595
Yes, he had that.

1397
01:00:32,662 --> 01:00:34,030
He had pastry.

1398
01:00:34,597 --> 01:00:36,099
SUNG-JUN GETS
THE SANDWICH INGREDIENTS READY

1399
01:00:36,666 --> 01:00:39,636
5. SEASON CROISSANT, CHERRY TOMATOES,
CHICKEN BREAST AND CHEESE

1400
01:00:39,702 --> 01:00:42,672
WITH BLACK PEPPER,
OLIVE OIL AND SUGAR

1401
01:00:43,840 --> 01:00:48,044
They're making in-flight meals
with ingredients only from DEX's fridge.

1402
01:00:48,111 --> 01:00:49,112
Soy sauce.

1403
01:00:49,178 --> 01:00:50,046
ONE DRIP

1404
01:00:50,113 --> 01:00:51,781
Soy sauce.

1405
01:00:51,848 --> 01:00:53,116
He's using a lot of soy sauce.

1406
01:00:53,182 --> 01:00:55,184
-Wouldn't it be too salty?
-Oh, my.

1407
01:00:55,251 --> 01:00:56,686
That looks too salty.

1408
01:00:56,753 --> 01:00:58,521
You know, DEX may end up

1409
01:00:58,588 --> 01:01:01,224
falling asleep without eating
your in-flight meals.

1410
01:01:02,592 --> 01:01:05,495
I didn't expect to do that.
Then, I'll need some cup noodles.

1411
01:01:05,561 --> 01:01:06,796
Right?

1412
01:01:07,497 --> 01:01:10,366
If you can't finish it,
you have to make some <i>ramyeon</i>.

1413
01:01:10,433 --> 01:01:11,734
7. MAKE SAUCE
BY BOILING GREEN ONION OIL,

1414
01:01:11,801 --> 01:01:13,102
SOY SAUCE, WATER,
COOKING WINE AND SUGAR

1415
01:01:13,169 --> 01:01:14,604
THE BLOOD SUGAR SPIKE PLAN?

1416
01:01:14,671 --> 01:01:16,539
Why did you put in so much sugar?

1417
01:01:17,106 --> 01:01:18,675
Oh, he's taking some out.

1418
01:01:19,642 --> 01:01:21,778
He put in too much sugar.

1419
01:01:21,844 --> 01:01:24,080
-That was a lot.
-Yes.

1420
01:01:24,147 --> 01:01:25,682
It looks like Da-hee is thinking,

1421
01:01:25,748 --> 01:01:28,618
"I'm so glad that's not my fridge."

1422
01:01:29,419 --> 01:01:32,755
8. BRAISE FRIED SIRLOIN IN THE SAUCE
AND FINISH MONGOLIAN BEEF

1423
01:01:32,822 --> 01:01:34,991
-Six minutes.
-Six minutes?

1424
01:01:35,058 --> 01:01:38,027
The flight from Milan
is about to serve Western cuisine.

1425
01:01:38,094 --> 01:01:39,095
CHEESE

1426
01:01:40,797 --> 01:01:43,132
-Chef Sung-jun, what's the cut?
-Yes?

1427
01:01:43,199 --> 01:01:44,200
Tenderloin.

1428
01:01:44,267 --> 01:01:47,070
Tenderloin. Poong used sirloin,

1429
01:01:47,136 --> 01:01:49,038
and Sung-jun is using tenderloin.

1430
01:01:50,006 --> 01:01:53,142
-Look at that.
-He's running around.

1431
01:01:53,209 --> 01:01:56,145
6. COAT TENDERLOIN AND COOKED POTATO
WITH GREEK YOGURT AND FRYING POWDER,

1432
01:01:56,212 --> 01:01:58,781
THEN DEEP-FRY

1433
01:01:59,449 --> 01:02:03,720
FRIED POTATOES AND MEAT
IS ALWAYS GOOD

1434
01:02:05,888 --> 01:02:07,590
When will you add the perilla leaves?

1435
01:02:08,191 --> 01:02:09,325
POONG FISHES OUT
THE SHRIMP HEADS

1436
01:02:09,392 --> 01:02:11,060
He's taking out the shrimp heads.

1437
01:02:11,127 --> 01:02:12,595
That's right.
He said he wouldn't keep those.

1438
01:02:12,662 --> 01:02:14,230
It looks good.

1439
01:02:14,297 --> 01:02:16,899
-And perilla leaves? It's going in.
-It's going in.

1440
01:02:17,633 --> 01:02:20,136
-Is he just pulling those apart?
-He's putting them in just like that?

1441
01:02:20,203 --> 01:02:21,971
INTERESTING - SUSPICIOUS

1442
01:02:22,038 --> 01:02:23,973
-He didn't even blend it or anything.
-I know. It's soup.

1443
01:02:24,040 --> 01:02:25,842
-Chicken stock.
-Chicken stock.

1444
01:02:25,908 --> 01:02:26,909
Chicken stock.

1445
01:02:26,976 --> 01:02:27,977
IT HAS TO BE GOOD

1446
01:02:28,044 --> 01:02:29,512
That has to be good now.

1447
01:02:29,579 --> 01:02:31,647
So you're leaving solid ingredients in?

1448
01:02:31,714 --> 01:02:33,649
What's he doing?

1449
01:02:34,183 --> 01:02:35,184
He's blending it right away?

1450
01:02:35,251 --> 01:02:37,987
-He's blending it like that.
-In the pot.

1451
01:02:38,054 --> 01:02:40,289
HE BLENDS IT RIGHT IN THE POT!

1452
01:02:40,356 --> 01:02:41,491
He doesn't have enough time.

1453
01:02:41,557 --> 01:02:45,194
The leaves will crumple up
if he doesn't blend it.

1454
01:02:45,261 --> 01:02:47,330
I wonder what that soup will taste like.

1455
01:02:47,396 --> 01:02:48,631
I'm curious.

1456
01:02:48,698 --> 01:02:52,235
He could've put it in a blender
and worked on something else.

1457
01:02:54,604 --> 01:02:56,572
He would've been a chef if he knew that.

1458
01:02:56,639 --> 01:02:57,740
OH!

1459
01:02:57,807 --> 01:03:00,510
-He almost spilled it.
-There's turbulence.

1460
01:03:03,079 --> 01:03:04,614
He almost spilled it.

1461
01:03:04,680 --> 01:03:05,681
Poong, the oven.

1462
01:03:05,748 --> 01:03:08,518
-Rice.
-They're cooking on a plane right now.

1463
01:03:08,584 --> 01:03:11,721
HE HEATS UP INSTANT RICE,
AND THE ROUND IS IN THE LAST PHASE!

1464
01:03:12,288 --> 01:03:15,825
You have five minutes left.
Jung-hwan, please go out on the field.

1465
01:03:15,892 --> 01:03:17,360
-Flight Attendant Ahn, please go.
-All right.

1466
01:03:17,426 --> 01:03:18,427
I'll go now.

1467
01:03:18,494 --> 01:03:20,229
We, at <i>Chef & My Fridge</i> Air,
will do our best

1468
01:03:20,296 --> 01:03:23,299
to serve our in-flight meals to our guest.

1469
01:03:23,366 --> 01:03:24,834
May I use the oven?

1470
01:03:24,901 --> 01:03:27,136
-What are these?
-Potatoes and…

1471
01:03:27,203 --> 01:03:29,705
-Are you frying potatoes? And beef?
-Potatoes and beef.

1472
01:03:29,772 --> 01:03:31,774
The potato isn't fully submerged
in the oil.

1473
01:03:31,841 --> 01:03:34,343
You're right. But Sung-jun can't hear you.

1474
01:03:34,410 --> 01:03:36,879
The potatoes aren't fully in the oil yet.

1475
01:03:37,647 --> 01:03:38,648
What's wrong? What?

1476
01:03:38,714 --> 01:03:40,583
He's taking out Poong's bread.

1477
01:03:40,650 --> 01:03:43,820
Wait, what? Did it not go well?
Is the bread not ready?

1478
01:03:43,886 --> 01:03:45,688
-Press it again.
-Press start!

1479
01:03:46,589 --> 01:03:48,157
-I got it.
-You got it?

1480
01:03:48,224 --> 01:03:50,393
-The potatoes aren't in the oil.
-He's frying beef and potatoes.

1481
01:03:50,459 --> 01:03:53,329
THE POTATOES GO INTO THE OIL

1482
01:03:53,396 --> 01:03:54,797
That's the perilla leaf soup.

1483
01:03:54,864 --> 01:03:58,100
This is… I don't know what it is.
It's Mongolian what?

1484
01:03:58,167 --> 01:04:00,102
-Mongolian beef.
-Mongolian beef over rice.

1485
01:04:00,169 --> 01:04:03,306
It's Mongolian beef over rice,
but I'm not so sure yet.

1486
01:04:03,372 --> 01:04:05,575
-All done.
-What about the rice?

1487
01:04:05,641 --> 01:04:06,776
-I'm heating it up.
-You are?

1488
01:04:06,843 --> 01:04:09,011
You have to make <i>kouign-amann</i>.

1489
01:04:09,078 --> 01:04:10,246
I'm sorry, but what about the dessert?

1490
01:04:10,313 --> 01:04:11,514
Damn it.

1491
01:04:11,581 --> 01:04:12,849
"Damn it"?

1492
01:04:16,452 --> 01:04:17,820
"Damn it"?

1493
01:04:17,887 --> 01:04:19,856
THE ATHLETE CAN GET SCARY
WHEN HE'S MAD

1494
01:04:20,690 --> 01:04:22,859
-"Damn it"?
-No.

1495
01:04:22,925 --> 01:04:25,027
-"Damn it"?
-No, I meant calm down.

1496
01:04:25,094 --> 01:04:28,631
-Calm down? Who's going to calm down?
-Okay. Fine. All right.

1497
01:04:28,698 --> 01:04:30,600
-I'll calm down.
-Okay.

1498
01:04:30,666 --> 01:04:33,803
-Do you think the hosts are a joke?
-No.

1499
01:04:33,870 --> 01:04:35,171
Come on. Damn it.

1500
01:04:36,239 --> 01:04:37,340
Well, this is offensive.

1501
01:04:38,708 --> 01:04:40,142
Seriously.

1502
01:04:40,610 --> 01:04:41,611
-Three minutes.
-Three minutes.

1503
01:04:41,677 --> 01:04:43,713
-Three minutes.
-I doubt he can make the dessert.

1504
01:04:43,779 --> 01:04:45,448
Oh, no.

1505
01:04:45,514 --> 01:04:46,782
Will he be able to do it?

1506
01:04:46,849 --> 01:04:48,718
You only have three minutes left.

1507
01:04:48,784 --> 01:04:51,020
You have three minutes left.

1508
01:04:51,087 --> 01:04:53,456
ANOTHER BLOOD SUGAR SPIKE?

1509
01:04:53,856 --> 01:04:54,857
10. MELT BUTTER AND SUGAR,

1510
01:04:54,924 --> 01:04:56,592
THEN TOAST A HOT DOG BUN IN IT,
MAKE KOUIGN-AMANN

1511
01:04:56,659 --> 01:04:59,328
-I told you, didn't I?
-He's just putting sugar on the bread.

1512
01:05:01,998 --> 01:05:02,999
Where did he get that?

1513
01:05:03,065 --> 01:05:04,166
Where did he get that?

1514
01:05:04,233 --> 01:05:05,835
-Oh, wow.
-The in-flight meal plates.

1515
01:05:05,902 --> 01:05:08,170
That's what I'm talking about!

1516
01:05:08,237 --> 01:05:09,639
Gosh, Sung-jun.

1517
01:05:09,705 --> 01:05:11,040
These?

1518
01:05:11,107 --> 01:05:15,011
You got this bottle of water.
You've got a whole meal on a plate.

1519
01:05:15,077 --> 01:05:16,746
MOUTH-WATERING

1520
01:05:17,313 --> 01:05:20,283
PREPARING DICED KIWI

1521
01:05:20,349 --> 01:05:21,751
What's this?

1522
01:05:21,817 --> 01:05:22,885
Polenta.

1523
01:05:22,952 --> 01:05:24,053
That looks about done.

1524
01:05:24,120 --> 01:05:26,389
Shouldn't you check on the potatoes?

1525
01:05:26,455 --> 01:05:27,456
They're fine.

1526
01:05:28,591 --> 01:05:29,592
They're fine.

1527
01:05:29,659 --> 01:05:31,327
He's making perilla leaf soup.

1528
01:05:31,394 --> 01:05:32,728
-Hey, Jung-hwan!
-Yes?

1529
01:05:32,795 --> 01:05:34,964
-Try some perilla leaf soup.
-Should I?

1530
01:05:35,031 --> 01:05:36,098
Perilla leaf soup.

1531
01:05:36,165 --> 01:05:38,367
AN INTERIM CHECK
ON THE PERILLA SOUP!

1532
01:05:38,868 --> 01:05:39,969
SLURP

1533
01:05:40,036 --> 01:05:42,638
How does it taste?

1534
01:05:42,705 --> 01:05:44,006
HMM…

1535
01:05:44,607 --> 01:05:46,575
WAS THAT A SPOILER?

1536
01:05:46,642 --> 01:05:47,710
Should he just sleep?

1537
01:05:48,344 --> 01:05:50,313
I don't think I can fall asleep.

1538
01:05:50,379 --> 01:05:51,847
Why not? Is it bad?

1539
01:05:51,914 --> 01:05:54,116
-It's peculiar.
-It tastes peculiar?

1540
01:05:54,183 --> 01:05:56,652
It should smell more like perilla leaf.
But it's seasoned properly.

1541
01:05:56,719 --> 01:05:59,121
-It'll taste fine with bread.
-I see.

1542
01:05:59,188 --> 01:06:00,356
I didn't eat it with bread.

1543
01:06:00,923 --> 01:06:03,459
So the perilla leaf smell
isn't too strong.

1544
01:06:03,526 --> 01:06:04,527
The barbecue…

1545
01:06:05,394 --> 01:06:06,762
Damn it.

1546
01:06:07,763 --> 01:06:09,632
STIR-FRY DEEP-FRIED SIRLOIN
AND POTATOES

1547
01:06:09,699 --> 01:06:11,867
WITH BUTTER AND BARBECUE SAUCE

1548
01:06:15,071 --> 01:06:16,706
POONG OPENS THE INSTANT RICE!

1549
01:06:16,772 --> 01:06:18,140
A minute and 40 seconds.

1550
01:06:18,207 --> 01:06:19,775
A minute and 40 seconds? Shit.

1551
01:06:19,842 --> 01:06:20,876
He's serving rice.

1552
01:06:20,943 --> 01:06:22,478
HE SETS THE RICE IN THE BOWL

1553
01:06:22,545 --> 01:06:24,814
-A minute and 40 seconds.
-Oh, shit.

1554
01:06:25,881 --> 01:06:28,084
SUNG-JUN HASN'T STARTED
ON THE SANDWICH

1555
01:06:28,150 --> 01:06:30,086
What now? He took it out of the oven.

1556
01:06:30,152 --> 01:06:32,521
-The bread.
-Damn it.

1557
01:06:32,588 --> 01:06:33,823
HE HAS NOWHERE TO PUT IT DOWN

1558
01:06:34,390 --> 01:06:35,691
HE'S GOING CRAZY

1559
01:06:35,758 --> 01:06:38,461
-Your bread. Your bread.
-My bread?

1560
01:06:38,527 --> 01:06:39,895
Man! My bread! Wait.

1561
01:06:39,962 --> 01:06:43,199
-They're cursing left and right.
-Wait.

1562
01:06:43,265 --> 01:06:45,101
What now?
Are you both trying to calm down?

1563
01:06:45,167 --> 01:06:47,136
They're both going, "Damn it."

1564
01:06:47,203 --> 01:06:49,705
"Damn it." Yes, damn me.

1565
01:06:49,772 --> 01:06:52,575
Wait. Damn it.

1566
01:06:52,641 --> 01:06:54,110
Man!

1567
01:06:54,176 --> 01:06:55,344
LOSING HIS MIND AND LAUGHING?

1568
01:06:55,411 --> 01:06:56,946
I'm running out of time.

1569
01:06:58,381 --> 01:07:01,584
It seems to me
that the flight hasn't even taken off.

1570
01:07:01,650 --> 01:07:04,420
Flights only take off
after the in-flight meals are loaded.

1571
01:07:04,487 --> 01:07:06,355
-You have a minute.
-One minute.

1572
01:07:06,422 --> 01:07:08,991
One minute. Sung-jun is in a mess too.

1573
01:07:09,058 --> 01:07:10,359
In-flight meals are harder than it looks.

1574
01:07:10,426 --> 01:07:13,462
-They said Sung-jun is a mess.
-Oh, no.

1575
01:07:16,298 --> 01:07:17,633
Where's the plate? Damn it.

1576
01:07:17,700 --> 01:07:19,101
He's serving it.

1577
01:07:19,168 --> 01:07:20,636
10. MAKE THE SANDWICH WITH CROISSANT,
DEX SAUCE, CHICKEN BREAST, CHEESE, LETTUCE

1578
01:07:20,703 --> 01:07:22,271
POONG GRABS LETTUCE TOO

1579
01:07:22,338 --> 01:07:24,340
We need the in-flight meals to take off.

1580
01:07:24,407 --> 01:07:25,908
He just threw the lettuce in there.

1581
01:07:25,975 --> 01:07:27,343
Why did he add the lettuce?

1582
01:07:27,410 --> 01:07:29,645
-Look at the lettuce.
-What are you doing?

1583
01:07:29,712 --> 01:07:31,881
What's that? Oh, no.

1584
01:07:32,515 --> 01:07:33,516
Is that right?

1585
01:07:34,150 --> 01:07:35,818
I don't know what's going on.

1586
01:07:35,885 --> 01:07:37,753
Thirty seconds!

1587
01:07:37,820 --> 01:07:40,056
-What is this, Poong?
-Thirty seconds.

1588
01:07:41,123 --> 01:07:42,324
You're in a rush.

1589
01:07:42,391 --> 01:07:44,960
-Thirty seconds.
-Damn it.

1590
01:07:45,027 --> 01:07:46,495
Thirty seconds.

1591
01:07:46,562 --> 01:07:48,030
POLENTA IS FINISHED

1592
01:07:48,097 --> 01:07:49,198
Wait.

1593
01:07:50,699 --> 01:07:53,335
-You're in a rush.
-Damn it.

1594
01:07:53,402 --> 01:07:57,540
TOPPING IT WITH BEEF
AND POTATO STIR-FRY

1595
01:07:58,407 --> 01:08:00,643
What is this, Poong?

1596
01:08:00,709 --> 01:08:02,678
Oh, no.

1597
01:08:02,745 --> 01:08:06,015
MONGOLIAN BEEF IS FINISHED

1598
01:08:06,082 --> 01:08:08,084
-Twenty seconds.
-Twenty seconds.

1599
01:08:08,150 --> 01:08:10,453
No! My bread!

1600
01:08:11,620 --> 01:08:14,090
-It's burnt.
-No! My bread!

1601
01:08:14,156 --> 01:08:15,591
RUINED KOUIGN-AMANN

1602
01:08:15,658 --> 01:08:17,293
-The bread!
-The bread!

1603
01:08:18,661 --> 01:08:20,696
The bread is burnt. It's a mess here!

1604
01:08:20,763 --> 01:08:22,598
-Ten, nine,
-Oh, no.

1605
01:08:22,665 --> 01:08:24,800
-eight, seven.
-It's hot!

1606
01:08:25,367 --> 01:08:26,769
What will you serve?

1607
01:08:26,836 --> 01:08:31,006
What will you do? The dessert.

1608
01:08:31,073 --> 01:08:32,641
THE YOGURT ICE CREAM
HE PUT IN EARLIER

1609
01:08:33,642 --> 01:08:35,177
10. STACK ICE CREAM, GREEK YOGURT,
KIWI, AND CHOCOLATE BALLS IN ORDER

1610
01:08:35,244 --> 01:08:38,114
-No! My bread!
-The bread!

1611
01:08:38,180 --> 01:08:40,182
-It's burnt.
-No! My bread!

1612
01:08:40,249 --> 01:08:42,451
HIS DESSERT IS FINISHED

1613
01:08:42,518 --> 01:08:45,121
Nine, eight, seven…

1614
01:08:45,187 --> 01:08:48,757
-Knife.
-What will you serve?

1615
01:08:48,824 --> 01:08:51,794
-Three, two, one.
-The bread!

1616
01:08:51,861 --> 01:08:54,130
Wait, why are you serving plain bread?

1617
01:08:55,431 --> 01:08:58,868
-Three, two, one.
-The bread!

1618
01:08:58,934 --> 01:09:00,302
-Time's up!
-The bread.

1619
01:09:00,369 --> 01:09:02,538
-Ring the bell.
-It's over!

1620
01:09:02,605 --> 01:09:03,606
Sung-jun is done.

1621
01:09:03,672 --> 01:09:05,074
Man, this is…

1622
01:09:06,242 --> 01:09:08,010
KIM POONG FINISHES
ATTENTION POONG-LEASE

1623
01:09:08,077 --> 01:09:12,314
-My gosh.
-Did you put something on that bread?

1624
01:09:12,381 --> 01:09:15,751
Hey, wait. You can't just serve
plain bread like this.

1625
01:09:15,818 --> 01:09:18,387
-He just served plain bread in half.
-What is this?

1626
01:09:18,454 --> 01:09:20,556
You can't just serve bread like this.

1627
01:09:20,623 --> 01:09:22,825
What kind of an airline is this?

1628
01:09:22,892 --> 01:09:24,326
THEY SOMEHOW FINISHED
THE IN-FLIGHT MEALS

1629
01:09:24,827 --> 01:09:25,995
-Wait.
-Look.

1630
01:09:26,061 --> 01:09:27,596
Put the bread you toasted in the oven.

1631
01:09:27,663 --> 01:09:29,632
Give me the bread.
This is the <i>kouign-amann</i>.

1632
01:09:29,698 --> 01:09:31,333
How is that the <i>kouign-amann</i>?

1633
01:09:31,400 --> 01:09:34,003
That's a dinner roll.

1634
01:09:34,069 --> 01:09:35,271
Can you grab that piece of bread?

1635
01:09:35,337 --> 01:09:37,940
-Push it up.
-Push it up.

1636
01:09:38,007 --> 01:09:40,142
-We have to fly.
-We have no way around it.

1637
01:09:40,209 --> 01:09:41,610
-He'll have to eat it.
-Oh, no.

1638
01:09:41,677 --> 01:09:43,379
TAKEN ABACK

1639
01:09:43,445 --> 01:09:45,548
The turbulence must've been pretty bad.

1640
01:09:46,348 --> 01:09:48,317
-There was turbulence.
-Yes.

1641
01:09:49,485 --> 01:09:54,790
And now, the in-flight meals
are all finished for DEX.

1642
01:09:54,857 --> 01:09:58,928
Thank you for flying
with <i>Chef & My Fridge</i> Air.

1643
01:09:58,994 --> 01:10:00,696
-He's our purser.
-I see.

1644
01:10:00,763 --> 01:10:02,298
-The purser.
-He'll serve you himself.

1645
01:10:02,364 --> 01:10:06,135
This is the in-flight meal
served on a flight from Milan.

1646
01:10:06,202 --> 01:10:07,436
It's dinner.

1647
01:10:07,503 --> 01:10:10,673
Our top chef prepared
the best dish for you.

1648
01:10:10,739 --> 01:10:13,542
-Look how classy it is.
-Yes. Give him a fork.

1649
01:10:13,609 --> 01:10:15,678
You're right. Look at the service.

1650
01:10:15,744 --> 01:10:18,347
-Why, of course.
-Here you go.

1651
01:10:18,414 --> 01:10:19,848
You're so kind.

1652
01:10:22,151 --> 01:10:23,485
Enjoy.

1653
01:10:25,054 --> 01:10:30,192
FRIED MEAT AND POTATOES
ON TOP OF POLENTA

1654
01:10:30,826 --> 01:10:32,861
SANDWICH MADE TO HIS TASTE

1655
01:10:32,928 --> 01:10:35,798
AND A SWEET DESSERT

1656
01:10:36,298 --> 01:10:40,236
CHEF KWON SUNG-JUN'S MILAN MATFIA

1657
01:10:40,302 --> 01:10:42,271
Should I try the bread first?

1658
01:10:42,338 --> 01:10:45,674
-Please try the polenta and meat first.
-The meat first.

1659
01:10:45,741 --> 01:10:48,244
It's topped with fried potatoes
and tenderloin coated in barbecue sauce

1660
01:10:48,310 --> 01:10:51,113
served with polenta below.

1661
01:10:51,180 --> 01:10:53,449
-Okay, then.
-Let's have him try it.

1662
01:10:53,515 --> 01:10:56,685
I was wondering
if the potatoes were fully cooked.

1663
01:10:56,752 --> 01:11:01,557
Everything looks well-put together
compared to how big of a mess it was.

1664
01:11:01,624 --> 01:11:04,093
My gosh. So?

1665
01:11:04,159 --> 01:11:05,861
-Polenta.
-Is it good?

1666
01:11:05,928 --> 01:11:09,098
I hope our guest likes it.

1667
01:11:09,164 --> 01:11:12,368
-Do you like it?
-That good?

1668
01:11:12,434 --> 01:11:14,903
-Gosh, the potatoes.
-What about them?

1669
01:11:14,970 --> 01:11:17,840
I thought the potato was the meat.

1670
01:11:17,906 --> 01:11:20,709
It felt a bit like
I was chewing on chicken,

1671
01:11:20,776 --> 01:11:22,611
but it turned out to be a piece of potato.

1672
01:11:22,678 --> 01:11:25,047
I see. Polenta.

1673
01:11:25,114 --> 01:11:28,651
That was a mix of tenderloin and potatoes.

1674
01:11:28,717 --> 01:11:29,818
-Gosh.
-Is it good?

1675
01:11:29,885 --> 01:11:32,054
-It's the kind of in-flight meal I wanted.
-Really?

1676
01:11:33,255 --> 01:11:35,057
He looks satisfied.

1677
01:11:35,124 --> 01:11:36,725
How is it so thick?

1678
01:11:36,792 --> 01:11:40,429
How did you make this with the soup?
I love how thick it is.

1679
01:11:40,496 --> 01:11:44,500
I boiled down crushed garlic,
onion, and butter,

1680
01:11:44,566 --> 01:11:46,835
then made it thicker with cheese.

1681
01:11:46,902 --> 01:11:49,271
So the corn soup powder
was used in this sauce, right?

1682
01:11:49,338 --> 01:11:51,206
Yes, I made it with corn soup powder.

1683
01:11:52,174 --> 01:11:56,545
He looks like a businessman.

1684
01:11:56,612 --> 01:11:59,415
Look at him. A young businessman.

1685
01:11:59,481 --> 01:12:01,850
HE HAS GOOD TABLE MANNERS

1686
01:12:01,917 --> 01:12:02,918
Look at him.

1687
01:12:02,985 --> 01:12:04,820
I have to show good etiquette.

1688
01:12:04,887 --> 01:12:07,356
He found success in his thirties.

1689
01:12:07,423 --> 01:12:09,358
I heard he's in the textile industry.

1690
01:12:09,425 --> 01:12:11,193
-Leather, to be precise.
-Leather, huh?

1691
01:12:11,260 --> 01:12:13,762
-I got this in Milan.
-That leather jacket.

1692
01:12:13,829 --> 01:12:15,431
There's a lot going on
inside the sandwich.

1693
01:12:15,497 --> 01:12:17,566
That's a sandwich.

1694
01:12:17,633 --> 01:12:21,870
I put in some chicken breast,
DEX sauce, made just for you,

1695
01:12:21,937 --> 01:12:24,139
cherry peppers, and lettuce.

1696
01:12:24,206 --> 01:12:25,774
It's a hearty sandwich.

1697
01:12:25,841 --> 01:12:26,975
It sure is.

1698
01:12:28,110 --> 01:12:31,480
-It sure is. It might fall apart.
-It looks good.

1699
01:12:32,381 --> 01:12:36,118
A BIG BITE

1700
01:12:36,185 --> 01:12:39,054
-It looks good.
-He makes it look good.

1701
01:12:41,223 --> 01:12:42,725
What's in the sauce?

1702
01:12:42,791 --> 01:12:47,129
The two key ingredients are yogurt
and his favorite sauce, mustard.

1703
01:12:47,196 --> 01:12:48,597
-Mustard?
-Mustard.

1704
01:12:48,664 --> 01:12:50,833
-Did you add sriracha too?
-I did.

1705
01:12:50,899 --> 01:12:52,634
And I added sweetness with strawberry jam.

1706
01:12:52,701 --> 01:12:55,270
Look at the quality of that sandwich.

1707
01:12:55,337 --> 01:12:56,972
HE DIPS THE BREAD IN POLENTA

1708
01:12:57,039 --> 01:12:59,742
It must be good. He dipped it in polenta.

1709
01:12:59,808 --> 01:13:02,878
-I have to dip the bread in this.
-I see.

1710
01:13:03,846 --> 01:13:05,914
Yes, in the sauce.

1711
01:13:05,981 --> 01:13:07,216
SUCKING HIS FINGER TOO

1712
01:13:07,282 --> 01:13:09,318
That was such a satisfying meal.

1713
01:13:09,385 --> 01:13:14,256
It may look too greasy
because he added cheese and whatnot,

1714
01:13:14,323 --> 01:13:17,493
-but it isn't at all. It's such a wonder.
-Really?

1715
01:13:17,559 --> 01:13:20,496
This special sauce is amazing.

1716
01:13:20,562 --> 01:13:23,432
The sour taste in mustard and sriracha is…

1717
01:13:23,499 --> 01:13:25,267
The acidity? I put lime juice in too.

1718
01:13:25,334 --> 01:13:29,104
That acidity plays a part
and refreshes the palate.

1719
01:13:29,171 --> 01:13:32,574
-It's something I can eat forever.
-I see.

1720
01:13:32,641 --> 01:13:35,277
-Time for dessert.
-I'll eat the dessert.

1721
01:13:35,344 --> 01:13:36,812
Take a big spoonful.

1722
01:13:36,879 --> 01:13:38,180
I see.

1723
01:13:38,247 --> 01:13:40,149
A BIG SPOONFUL

1724
01:13:40,215 --> 01:13:43,318
It'll be awesome
if they serve ice cream like that.

1725
01:13:44,887 --> 01:13:46,054
MMM

1726
01:13:47,823 --> 01:13:50,859
He mixed Greek yogurt with ice cream.

1727
01:13:50,926 --> 01:13:53,529
That rich flavor became a bit lighter

1728
01:13:53,595 --> 01:13:55,631
so that I could eat a lot of it.

1729
01:13:55,697 --> 01:14:00,035
Lastly, the kiwi adds a nice,
refreshing flavor.

1730
01:14:00,102 --> 01:14:03,071
That sounds wonderful.
It looks like you enjoyed it.

1731
01:14:04,540 --> 01:14:08,544
MONGOLIAN BEEF OVER RICE
SERVED IN A FLIGHT TO AMERICA

1732
01:14:09,111 --> 01:14:11,313
KIM POONG'S KOUIGN-AMANN

1733
01:14:11,380 --> 01:14:14,550
AND SOUP WITH K-HERB, PERILLA LEAF

1734
01:14:15,350 --> 01:14:17,586
WEBTOON ARTIST KIM POONG'S
ATTENTION POONG-LEASE

1735
01:14:17,653 --> 01:14:20,956
This time, we'll serve the in-flight meal

1736
01:14:21,023 --> 01:14:23,091
for a flight from Korea to America.

1737
01:14:23,158 --> 01:14:25,394
Actually, today is Eccentric Day,

1738
01:14:25,461 --> 01:14:27,796
-so we're serving an eccentric meal.
-I see.

1739
01:14:27,863 --> 01:14:30,132
We came across strong turbulence

1740
01:14:30,199 --> 01:14:32,768
-while the meal was being cooked.
-We couldn't help it.

1741
01:14:32,835 --> 01:14:35,704
I'm sorry. Please understand.

1742
01:14:35,771 --> 01:14:39,208
Think of the bread you see all around
as the appetizer bread.

1743
01:14:39,775 --> 01:14:40,809
HE CAN TELL RIGHT AWAY

1744
01:14:40,876 --> 01:14:42,444
-These?
-Yes.

1745
01:14:42,511 --> 01:14:44,580
-These?
-Yes.

1746
01:14:44,646 --> 01:14:46,415
-And soup.
-Try that with the soup.

1747
01:14:46,482 --> 01:14:48,951
He made the broth with shrimp heads

1748
01:14:49,017 --> 01:14:51,787
and added perilla leaves.

1749
01:14:51,854 --> 01:14:54,857
-It smells like shrimp.
-It does?

1750
01:14:55,624 --> 01:14:58,794
HE TAKES A CAUTIOUS BITE

1751
01:15:01,663 --> 01:15:03,565
There was strong turbulence.

1752
01:15:04,166 --> 01:15:05,968
LAUGHING

1753
01:15:06,034 --> 01:15:08,837
The pressure difference was high.

1754
01:15:08,904 --> 01:15:11,206
-No, it's good.
-It is?

1755
01:15:12,140 --> 01:15:13,509
I KNEW IT!

1756
01:15:14,176 --> 01:15:15,777
Is it good?

1757
01:15:15,844 --> 01:15:18,413
-It's really good.
-What?

1758
01:15:18,480 --> 01:15:19,781
-Really?
-Isn't the perilla leaf weird?

1759
01:15:19,848 --> 01:15:20,883
I mean it.

1760
01:15:20,949 --> 01:15:22,584
It must be good.

1761
01:15:22,651 --> 01:15:26,255
-It tastes like basil pasta.
-Because of the perilla leaf?

1762
01:15:26,321 --> 01:15:28,790
Did you use perilla leaf and cream?

1763
01:15:28,857 --> 01:15:31,827
I made some roux and added milk,

1764
01:15:31,894 --> 01:15:34,897
then I blended some perilla leaves.

1765
01:15:35,898 --> 01:15:37,966
He dips the bread in the soup.

1766
01:15:38,033 --> 01:15:39,268
That bread was good.

1767
01:15:39,334 --> 01:15:41,904
Hey, it must be crunchy.

1768
01:15:41,970 --> 01:15:44,473
It tastes just like in-flight bread.
Crunchy outside, soft inside.

1769
01:15:44,540 --> 01:15:46,108
IT'S PERFECT,
CRUNCHY OUTSIDE AND SOFT INSIDE

1770
01:15:46,174 --> 01:15:49,077
-Why is this good?
-"Why is this good?"

1771
01:15:49,144 --> 01:15:50,546
"Why is this good?"

1772
01:15:50,612 --> 01:15:53,949
Anyway, you were the first one to say
you liked our in-flight meal.

1773
01:15:54,016 --> 01:15:55,984
I found a shrimp whisker here.

1774
01:15:57,119 --> 01:15:58,987
-You win.
-He wins?

1775
01:15:59,054 --> 01:16:00,455
-You win.
-Was it an event?

1776
01:16:00,522 --> 01:16:03,358
-He gets another set of amenities.
-I see.

1777
01:16:06,395 --> 01:16:08,797
-The main dish.
-The rice.

1778
01:16:08,864 --> 01:16:13,335
Try the meat and the lettuce together.
It'll be delicious.

1779
01:16:13,402 --> 01:16:16,004
The lettuce looks too stale.

1780
01:16:16,071 --> 01:16:19,107
But it'll be crunchy.

1781
01:16:19,174 --> 01:16:22,611
That's Mongolian beef over rice.

1782
01:16:23,111 --> 01:16:24,479
It's crunchy.

1783
01:16:24,546 --> 01:16:26,214
-It is?
-Really?

1784
01:16:26,281 --> 01:16:29,151
Why is it crunchy?
I thought it was overcooked.

1785
01:16:29,217 --> 01:16:31,787
He didn't cook it all the way.
It was just cooked lightly.

1786
01:16:31,853 --> 01:16:34,022
-I fished it out.
-It'll taste crunchy and delicious.

1787
01:16:34,089 --> 01:16:35,090
-Really?
-Yes.

1788
01:16:36,158 --> 01:16:38,193
A BITE OF THE MEAT

1789
01:16:38,260 --> 01:16:41,296
DEX, I thought you'd be quite full.

1790
01:16:41,363 --> 01:16:42,931
THEN A BITE OF RICE

1791
01:16:42,998 --> 01:16:44,700
But he continues to eat.

1792
01:16:44,766 --> 01:16:47,202
-Why is this good?
-Is it good?

1793
01:16:47,269 --> 01:16:48,737
It's not tough at all.

1794
01:16:48,804 --> 01:16:50,906
Actually, the meat alone
is almost too salty.

1795
01:16:50,973 --> 01:16:52,774
But it's perfect with the rice.

1796
01:16:53,342 --> 01:16:56,144
-Because it's served over rice.
-It's served over rice.

1797
01:16:56,211 --> 01:16:57,446
YOU'RE RIGHT

1798
01:16:58,680 --> 01:17:00,849
-Something's odd.
-Something's odd?

1799
01:17:00,916 --> 01:17:02,951
-I feel sleepy now.
-You do?

1800
01:17:03,018 --> 01:17:05,854
-That's a success, then.
-That was his logic.

1801
01:17:05,921 --> 01:17:10,258
I'm getting sleepy,
so I'll try the dessert and take a nap.

1802
01:17:10,325 --> 01:17:12,194
This was the French dessert.

1803
01:17:12,260 --> 01:17:14,529
-This?
-Yes, the <i>kouign-amann</i>.

1804
01:17:14,596 --> 01:17:16,932
Is this a crushed shoe?

1805
01:17:16,999 --> 01:17:20,469
He tried to cut it,
but he ran out of time and threw it there.

1806
01:17:20,535 --> 01:17:22,537
This happens if you step on sneakers.

1807
01:17:22,604 --> 01:17:24,239
Who did this?

1808
01:17:24,306 --> 01:17:26,375
It looks like Charlie Chaplin's shoes.

1809
01:17:26,441 --> 01:17:27,809
I've never seen <i>kouign-amann </i>like that.

1810
01:17:27,876 --> 01:17:29,244
-<i>Kouign-amann</i>.
-<i>Kouign-amann</i>.

1811
01:17:29,311 --> 01:17:32,648
It's a type of pastry
that's crunchy and glazed with sugar.

1812
01:17:32,714 --> 01:17:34,583
He doesn't look too pleased.

1813
01:17:34,650 --> 01:17:36,051
It must be good.

1814
01:17:36,118 --> 01:17:38,220
The <i>kouign-amann</i>. It's ruined, right?

1815
01:17:38,286 --> 01:17:41,256
-Does it taste okay?
-Was it ruined?

1816
01:17:41,323 --> 01:17:43,425
-It must be good.
-Which is it?

1817
01:17:43,492 --> 01:17:45,293
-Hey, no way.
-Even the dessert must be good.

1818
01:17:45,360 --> 01:17:46,428
-It's good.
-Really?

1819
01:17:46,495 --> 01:17:48,430
-It is?
-Gosh.

1820
01:17:48,497 --> 01:17:50,332
-It's good.
-It is?

1821
01:17:50,399 --> 01:17:53,402
Gosh, I don't get it.

1822
01:17:53,468 --> 01:17:56,071
At first, it has this soft texture.

1823
01:17:56,138 --> 01:17:58,040
Then something in the middle
is hard and fun.

1824
01:17:58,974 --> 01:18:02,344
When you make <i>kouign-amann</i>,
you coat it with a sugar glaze.

1825
01:18:02,411 --> 01:18:05,881
So it's crunchy on the outside
and soft on the inside.

1826
01:18:05,947 --> 01:18:07,849
-It's the opposite.
-Oddly, yes.

1827
01:18:07,916 --> 01:18:09,951
THINKING OUTSIDE THE BOX
SOFT OUTSIDE, CRUNCHY INSIDE

1828
01:18:10,018 --> 01:18:11,319
You took it the other way.

1829
01:18:11,386 --> 01:18:13,488
Reversed <i>kouign-amann</i>.

1830
01:18:13,555 --> 01:18:15,323
-Reversed <i>kouign-amann</i>?
-Reversed?

1831
01:18:15,390 --> 01:18:17,559
Reversed <i>kouign-amann</i>.

1832
01:18:17,626 --> 01:18:21,663
-We serve reversed <i>kouign-amann</i>.
-Reversed?

1833
01:18:21,730 --> 01:18:23,298
Reversed <i>kouign-amann</i>.

1834
01:18:23,365 --> 01:18:24,966
The guests eats the food

1835
01:18:25,033 --> 01:18:30,172
and feels defeated by the cook
whenever they have Poong's food.

1836
01:18:30,238 --> 01:18:32,040
-I do feel defeated.
-I see.

1837
01:18:32,107 --> 01:18:34,209
I'm just wondering
how this turned out so delicious.

1838
01:18:34,276 --> 01:18:37,512
-I see. That's odd.
-That's strange.

1839
01:18:37,579 --> 01:18:40,849
Now, the flight from Milan to Korea

1840
01:18:40,916 --> 01:18:43,251
and the flight to America from Incheon.

1841
01:18:43,318 --> 01:18:45,153
Please choose one of the two.

1842
01:18:45,220 --> 01:18:48,557
Make your decision and press the button.

1843
01:18:49,791 --> 01:18:52,027
We now have no idea how this will end.

1844
01:18:52,094 --> 01:18:54,696
We all thought
Sung-jun would get an easy win,

1845
01:18:54,763 --> 01:18:57,299
but things have changed
after he tasted the food.

1846
01:18:59,367 --> 01:19:00,969
-Did you press it? He did.
-Yes.

1847
01:19:01,036 --> 01:19:03,271
All right. He decided.

1848
01:19:03,338 --> 01:19:07,609
Whose in-flight meal did DEX choose?

1849
01:19:07,676 --> 01:19:09,478
Let's find out the result!

1850
01:19:09,544 --> 01:19:10,545
Show us!

1851
01:19:10,612 --> 01:19:12,547
<i>Chef & My Fridge</i> Air in-flight meal.

1852
01:19:12,614 --> 01:19:15,784
Kim Poong's in-flight meal
on a flight from Korea to the USA.

1853
01:19:15,851 --> 01:19:19,087
Kwon Sung-jun's in-flight meal
on a flight from Milan to Korea.

1854
01:19:19,154 --> 01:19:23,992
Which in-flight meal did DEX choose?

1855
01:19:24,059 --> 01:19:26,528
Who's the winner?

1856
01:19:27,796 --> 01:19:30,298
The winner is…

1857
01:19:30,365 --> 01:19:32,934
KIM POONG WINS

1858
01:19:33,001 --> 01:19:34,002
The winner is…

1859
01:19:34,069 --> 01:19:36,738
WEBTOON ARTIST KIM POONG'S
ATTENTION POONG-LEASE WINS

1860
01:19:36,805 --> 01:19:38,607
-Kim Poong!
-This is huge!

1861
01:19:38,673 --> 01:19:40,408
AN UNBELIEVABLE RESULT

1862
01:19:40,475 --> 01:19:42,177
I can't believe this.

1863
01:19:42,744 --> 01:19:44,346
PATTING

1864
01:19:44,412 --> 01:19:46,381
-But this is…
-Really?

1865
01:19:47,115 --> 01:19:48,884
That was a huge twist.

1866
01:19:48,950 --> 01:19:51,219
At first, I thought

1867
01:19:51,286 --> 01:19:55,891
Poong served me leftovers.

1868
01:19:55,957 --> 01:19:59,594
But when I tried it,
it had a completely different taste,

1869
01:19:59,661 --> 01:20:02,130
-so I think I fell in shock.
-I see.

1870
01:20:02,197 --> 01:20:04,065
-Yes, that's why.
-There was a twist.

1871
01:20:04,132 --> 01:20:08,737
The problem was that I couldn't remember
what I had before this.

1872
01:20:08,804 --> 01:20:10,672
Thank you very much for enjoying it.

1873
01:20:10,739 --> 01:20:13,441
As I said before, in-flight meals
are all about that blood sugar spike.

1874
01:20:14,009 --> 01:20:15,911
You're right. I'm a little sleepy.

1875
01:20:15,977 --> 01:20:18,647
Please put a star on Poong.

1876
01:20:18,713 --> 01:20:20,348
This is his second win.

1877
01:20:21,116 --> 01:20:22,584
He's slowly rising.

1878
01:20:23,285 --> 01:20:25,720
-Poong is on the rise with two wins.
-Two wins in a row.

1879
01:20:25,787 --> 01:20:27,756
Congratulations!

1880
01:20:27,823 --> 01:20:29,925
Please welcome today's fridge owners!

1881
01:20:29,991 --> 01:20:32,227
We present Cha Jun-hwan
and Jung Jae-hyung.

1882
01:20:32,294 --> 01:20:34,496
Look at that. How does he hold out?

1883
01:20:34,563 --> 01:20:36,665
-Like that.
-He's the silly fairy.

1884
01:20:36,731 --> 01:20:37,933
MEETS THE SILLY FAIRY

1885
01:20:37,999 --> 01:20:40,769
I'm in a sport
that requires a strict diet.

1886
01:20:40,836 --> 01:20:42,871
-You eat only half of this?
-I rarely eat rice.

1887
01:20:42,938 --> 01:20:45,207
I get a little in my meal box,
about ten pieces.

1888
01:20:45,273 --> 01:20:46,408
-Ten pieces?
-You won the gold medal

1889
01:20:46,474 --> 01:20:47,876
after eating like this?

1890
01:20:47,943 --> 01:20:50,245
Today is my cheat day.

1891
01:20:50,312 --> 01:20:51,980
This is a cook-off for Cha Jun-hwan.

1892
01:20:52,047 --> 01:20:54,616
-Look at him!
-Hey!

1893
01:20:54,683 --> 01:20:56,017
It's the Olympics.

1894
01:20:56,084 --> 01:20:58,620
-It's the torch relay.
-How many points? One point.

1895
01:20:58,687 --> 01:20:59,921
-Three points.
-Three points.

1896
01:20:59,988 --> 01:21:01,823
It went up to five points.

1897
01:21:01,890 --> 01:21:03,992
-He's overeating.
-It must be good.

1898
01:21:04,059 --> 01:21:05,360
It's really good.

1899
01:21:05,427 --> 01:21:08,163
I'll show you who the real madman is.
I can't lose this one.

1900
01:21:08,230 --> 01:21:11,199
A small fire show.
"Look at me! It's me, Choi Hyun-suk!"

1901
01:21:11,266 --> 01:21:12,901
Wait, the color's too…

1902
01:21:12,968 --> 01:21:14,069
Isn't that <i>doenjang</i>?

1903
01:21:14,135 --> 01:21:16,905
-No, you can't do that.
-This is insane.

1904
01:21:16,972 --> 01:21:18,974
-Oh, no.
-Wait.

1905
01:21:19,040 --> 01:21:20,709
-Wait.
-That's pure insanity.

1906
01:21:23,445 --> 01:21:26,548
-I want to make <i>sundae</i> for the squid.
-<i>Sundae </i>for squid?

1907
01:21:26,615 --> 01:21:28,884
-Wait.
-Who are you calling a squid?

1908
01:21:30,018 --> 01:21:32,721
-You get five points deducted.
-What are you saying?

1909
01:21:41,897 --> 01:21:46,902
Subtitle translation by: Eunsook Youn
